{"accepted":[{"assertion":"AI-contributions wiki claim — wiki: Formalization.","id":"vf_47fc6436c0899fac","trust":"signed","type":"theoretical"},{"assertion":"Erdős Problem #106 [status: falsifiable; formalized: no]. Draw $n$ squares inside the unit square with no common interior point. Let $f(n)$ be the maximum possible sum of the side-lengths of the squares. Is $f(k^2+1)=k$? Current best: Hal\\'{a}sz \\cite{Ha84} gives a construction that shows $f(k^2+2)\\geq k+\\frac{1}{k+1}$, and in general, for any $c\\geq 1$,\\[f(k^2+2c+1)\\geq k+\\frac{c}{k}\\]and\\[f(k^2+2c)\\geq k+\\frac{c}{k+1}.\\]Hal\\'{a}sz also considers the variants where we replace a square by a parallelogram or triangle. Erd\\H{o}s and Soifer \\cite{ErSo95} and Campbell and Staton \\cite{CaSt05} have conjectured that, in general, for any integer $-k<c<k$, $f(k^2+2c+1)=k+\\frac{c}{k}$, and proved the corresponding lower bound. Prize: no. Tags: geometry.","id":"vf_8708c4c47db9a04b","trust":"signed","type":"theoretical"},{"assertion":"Formal-Conjectures statement: FC 106 (PR #3422) [in-pr] https://github.com/google-deepmind/formal-conjectures/pull/3422.","id":"vf_9398106557a18291","trust":"signed","type":"theoretical"}],"accepted_activity":false,"activity":[],"activity_types":[],"attempt_count":0,"banked_attempt_count":0,"commits":[],"dependency_impact":"none","detail_url":"problems/106.json","draft_proposals":[],"edges":[{"evidence":"Problem identity derived from the accepted finding's pinned source anchor.","inferred":true,"relation":"describes","source":"vf_47fc6436c0899fac","source_root":"sha256:1faedc24f040a60a22177b456c74b969a61ce8836082297b1835797a57b4fa56","target":"erdos:106","trust":"signed"},{"evidence":"Problem identity derived from the accepted finding's pinned source anchor.","inferred":true,"relation":"describes","source":"vf_8708c4c47db9a04b","source_root":"sha256:1faedc24f040a60a22177b456c74b969a61ce8836082297b1835797a57b4fa56","target":"erdos:106","trust":"signed"},{"evidence":"Problem